<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-03-21T11:44:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-03-21T11:44:00-05:00" n="515" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d515">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">882.00/941: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Liberia (<persName corresp="#p_MCE1" type="from">Mitchell</persName>) to the
                                        <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Monrovia</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-03-21T16:00:00-00:44">March 21, 1932—4
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 9:27 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>39. In an endeavor to adjust the Kru Coast situation <persName corresp="#p_BE1">Barclay</persName> is sending a commission
                                composed of <persName corresp="#p_TWA1">Winthrop Travell</persName>,
                                one of the American loan officials, with Reverend <persName corresp="#p_RFAK1">F. A. K. Russel</persName>, a Grebo, and
                                    <persName corresp="#p_CJFB1">J. F. Coleman</persName>, editor of
                                the <hi rend="italic">Weekly Mirror</hi>, to investigate and report
                                on the alleged outrages. If conditions do not warrant the presence
                                of soldiers, the Government promises to withdraw them
                                immediately.</p>
                            <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_MCE1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Mitchell</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>